All BOC:<br><br>
I injured my back dragging a deer up a steep river bank...further injured it by being gallant and helping my daughter bag and recover hers.  I am in pain..big time.. but crawled out of bed to say something.<br><br>
Everyone on this site knows what a clown I can be at times. I have had so much fun with all of you..Slam Dunking a buddie is my favorite sport!  I feel no guilt over poking fun at any of you..but I'm having a problem with that little old lady that we have ridiculed.<br><br>
At first, I couldn't pull up the picture..knew it would be funny.  Laughed my butt off when I finally got an image.  Planned strategies to nail Cookie...Art blasted me.. and the rest, too.  I responded with some nonsense and things seemed to get funnier.<br><br>
But for some reason... when I went to bed, something haunted me.  I remembered the face of that elderly woman.  I saw a sense of patriotic devotion.. a stern resolve.  Her feeble old hand lifted in a salute hit buttons all over me.  I began to wonder who her husband(s), son(s), brother(s), father(s), may have been.  Have they died for me?  What was the motivation for her to demonstrate patriotic pride?  She looks old and weary...What brought her out to a function that called for a salute?  Am I one to ridicule the eldery.. make jest of old women?  I wonder what her medals are for?  What kind of service has she rendored in my behalf?  Certainly, she dates back to a time when values meant something.  I wonder if she is still alive?  What do her children and other loved ones think of her?<br>
Had it been a Jack Davis (Mad Magazine) type carricature, I would still be laughing.  Now, I am filled with shame for doing to her what others have done to me.  Mockery is a form of rejection that we have all known.  I am as guilty as anyone for making mirth at the expense of this old woman.<br>
Had it been a gag photo I would be still laughing.<br>
Humor is always at someone's expense.  I'd rather it be me or a bunch of tough BOCs than a proud, feeble old lady lending dignity to the institutions we all fought for.<br>
I am not inviting anyone to share my shame... I love each of you more than words can convey... I take great pleasure in the shots you take at me and one another...it is a form of acceptance and brotherhood.<br>
In my wild pursuit of humor and bonding I must be more careful in the future.  She is a sainted old lady..not my mother or sweetheart..but maybe somebody's elses...now or in the past.<br>
I can handle the pain in my back..perhaps better now that I have washed away some of the pain emanating from a stupid mistake on my part.<br>
I will crawl into bed and dream of ways to slam dunk each of you with the same intensity I feel for lifting each of you up!<br><br>

